* Autostart

This sets up Qtile to run the autostart scripts depending on which backend it uses.

#+begin_src python
@hook.subscribe.startup_once
def start_once():
    if qtile.core.name == "x11":
        # subprocess.call([home + '/.config/qtile/scripts/autostart-theme1.sh'])
        subprocess.Popen([home + '/.config/qtile/scripts/autostart-theme1.sh'])
        # lazy.screen.set_wallpaper([home + '/.config/qtile/wall.jpg'], mode=fill)
    elif qtile.core.name == "wayland":
        subprocess.Popen([home + '/.config/qtile/scripts/autostart-theme1-wayland.sh']),
        subprocess.Popen(lazy.reload_config()),
        lazy.screen.set_wallpaper([home + '/.config/qtile/wall.jpg'], mode=fill)

#+end_src

* Wayland Input Rules

When using the Wayland backend, this can be used to configure input devices.
This section sets up Wayland input rules, which includes reduced pointer acceleration for "type:pointer" because I use a trackball mouse.

#+begin_src python
wl_input_rules = {
   "1267:12477:ELAN1300:00 04F3:3047 Touchpad": InputConfig(left_handed=False, tap = True),
   "*": InputConfig(left_handed=False, pointer_accel=False, tap = True),
   "type:pointer": InputConfig(pointer_accel=-1.0),
   "type:keyboard": InputConfig(kb_layout="gb"),
}

#+end_src

* Dirty Hack for When Qtile uses the wrong resolution

While I no longer use this, it came in handy when I was using Qtile Wayland on NixOS and it was broken. I'm leaving this here for documentation purposes but as far as I know, it is no longer needed. 

#+begin_src python
lazy.spawn("wlr-randr --output X11-1 --on --custom-mode 1920x1080@60Hz")
lazy.reload_config(),

#+end_src

* Window Manager Name Hack

As the comments below suggest, this is a compatibility-based hack that isn't really that important, but it was in the default config so here it is.

#+begin_src python
# XXX: Gasp! We're lying here. In fact, nobody really uses or cares about this
# string besides java UI toolkits; you can see several discussions on the
# mailing lists, GitHub issues, and other WM documentation that suggest setting
# this string if your java app doesn't work correctly. We may as well just lie
# and say that we're a working one by default.
#
# We choose LG3D to maximize irony: it is a 3D non-reparenting WM written in
# java that happens to be on java's whitelist.
wmname = "LG3D"

#+end_src
